  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is a good book to learn Excel?",
  "response": "Here are some excellent books to learn Excel, catering to different skill levels and learning preferences:\n\n### **Beginner to Intermediate Level**\n1. **\"Excel for Dummies\" by Greg Harvey**  \n   - A great starting point for beginners. It covers the basics of Excel in an easy-to-understand way, including formulas, charts, and data organization.\n\n2. **\"Microsoft Excel 365 Bible\" by Michael Alexander and Dick Kusleika**  \n   - A comprehensive guide for Excel users, covering everything from beginner to advanced features. It\u2019s updated for Excel 365 and includes practical examples.\n\n3. **\"Excel 2021 & Microsoft 365 All-in-One For Dummies\" by Greg Harvey**  \n   - A detailed guide for newer versions of Excel, including Microsoft 365. It\u2019s perfect for learners who want to master Excel\u2019s latest features.\n\n4. **\"Learn Excel 365 Essential Skills with The Smart Method\" by Mike Smart**  \n   - A structured, step-by-step guide that teaches essential Excel skills using real-world examples. Ideal for beginners and those looking to refresh their knowledge.\n\n### **Intermediate to Advanced Level**\n5. **\"Excel Formulas and Functions For Dummies\" by Ken Bluttman**  \n   - Focuses on mastering Excel\u2019s formulas and functions, which are critical for data analysis and advanced tasks.\n\n6. **\"Power Excel with MrExcel: Master Pivot Tables, Subtotals, Charts, VLOOKUP, IF, Data Analysis in Minutes...\" by Bill Jelen**  \n   - A practical guide to mastering Excel\u2019s powerful features like pivot tables, VLOOKUP, and data analysis. Written in a conversational style.\n\n7. **\"Microsoft Excel Data Analysis and Business Modeling\" by Wayne Winston**  \n   - A must-read for those interested in using Excel for business analysis and modeling. It includes real-world case studies and advanced techniques.\n\n### **For Data Analysis and Visualization**\n8. **\"Data Visualization with Excel: Tools for Data-Driven Decision Making\" by Jordan Goldmeier and Purnachandra Duggirala**  \n   - Focuses on creating compelling data visualizations in Excel, making it ideal for professionals who need to present data effectively.\n\n9. **\"Excel Dashboards and Reports\" by Michael Alexander**  \n   - Teaches how to create dynamic dashboards and reports in Excel, perfect for data analysts and business professionals.\n\n### **For Programmers and Power Users**\n10. **\"Excel VBA Programming For Dummies\" by Michael Alexander and John Walkenbach**  \n    - A great introduction to automating Excel tasks with VBA (Visual Basic for Applications). Ideal for those who want to create macros and automate processes.\n\n11. **\"Mastering VBA for Microsoft Office 365\" by Richard Mansfield**  \n    - A deeper dive into VBA programming for advanced users who want to customize and automate Excel and other Office applications.\n\n### **Honorable Mentions**\n- **\"The Excel Guru: Instructions and Insights for Excel Users\" by John Michaloudis and Bryan Hong**  \n   - A practical guide with tips and tricks from Excel experts.  \n- **\"Excel Hacks: Tips & Tools for Streamlining Your Spreadsheets\" by David and Raina Hawley**  \n   - A collection of time-saving hacks for Excel users of all levels.\n\n### **Tips for Choosing:**\n- If you're a beginner, start with a \"For Dummies\" book or a beginner-friendly guide.  \n- If you're focused on data analysis, look for books that emphasize formulas, functions, and visualization.  \n- For advanced users, consider books on VBA, automation, or business modeling.\n\nPairing these books with hands-on practice will help you master Excel effectively!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
